{"event": "tool_result", "tool": "view", "is_error": false, "result": {"status": "success", "file": "C:\\QAx\\002\\artifacts\\outputs\\product-definition\\PRD-SPEC-RESEARCH-STARWARSLEGO-PRODUCTDEFINITION-20260703.md", "content": "1: ---\n2: version: 1.0.0\n3: session_id: RESEARCH-STARWARSLEGO-PRODUCTDEFINITION-20260703\n4: engagement_mode: greenfield\n5: skill: researching-prd\n6: generated_at: 2026-07-03T15:25:00.000Z\n7: ---\n8: \n9: # PRD SPEC: Star Wars Lego Educational Web Application\n10: \n11: ## Scope\n12: \n13: **Project Vision:** Create an engaging single-page web application that teaches JavaScript ES6+ and Vue.js 2.x concepts through interactive Star Wars Lego themed exercises.\n14: \n15: **Product Category:** Educational Technology - Interactive Programming Tutorial\n16: \n17: **Target Platform:** Web browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge) on desktop and tablet (820px+)\n18: \n19: **Out of Scope:** \n20: - Mobile applications (resolutions below 820px)\n21: - Backend/database integration\n22: - User authentication systems\n23: - Social media integration\n24: - Multiplayer features\n25: \n26: **Core Value Proposition:** Hands-on learning of modern web development through an engaging, themed interactive experience that bridges theory and practical application.\n27: \n28: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:6-14\n29: \n30: ## Personas\n31: \n32: ### P-01: Beginner JavaScript Student\n33: **Role:** Primary user learning programming fundamentals\n34: **Attributes:**\n35: - Age: 16-35\n36: - Technical level: Novice to beginner programmers\n37: - Learning goals: Master JavaScript ES6+ and Vue.js basics\n38: - Motivation: Career change, skill development, academic learning\n39: - Pain points: Abstract programming concepts, lack of engaging learning materials\n40: **Device usage:** Desktop computers, tablets for practice\n41: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:14-15\n42: \n43: ### P-02: Web Development Learner\n44: **Role:** Self-taught developer expanding skillset\n45: **Attributes:**\n46: - Age: 20-40\n47: - Technical level: Some HTML/CSS knowledge, limited JavaScript experience\n48: - Learning goals: Practical application of modern JavaScript frameworks\n49: - Motivation: Portfolio building, job preparation, hobby development\n50: - Pain points: Fragmented learning resources, lack of hands-on projects\n51: **Device usage:** Primary desktop, occasional tablet\n52: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:14-15\n53: \n54: ### P-03: Programming Educator\n55: **Role:** Teacher or instructor using the application as teaching tool\n56: **Attributes:**\n57: - Age: 25-55\n58: - Technical level: Experienced developer or educator\n59: - Learning goals: Teaching resources, demonstration materials\n60: - Motivation: Student engagement, effective teaching tools\n61: - Pain points: Finding engaging, practical examples for students\n62: **Device usage:** Desktop for classroom presentations\n63: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:14-15\n64: \n65: ## Functional Requirements\n66: \n67: ### FR-01: Character Gallery Display\n68: **Description:** Grid-based display of 8 classic Star Wars Lego characters with interactive hover effects and visual transitions.\n69: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n70: - given: user accesses the application\n71: - when: the main page loads\n72: - then: display 8 Star Wars Lego characters in a grid layout\n73: - given: user hovers over a character card\n74: - when: cursor enters the character area\n75: - then: show enhanced visual effects and transitions\n76: **Priority:** Must Have\n77: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:40-44\n78: \n79: ### FR-02: Character Search System\n80: **Description:** Real-time filtering functionality to search characters by name with input validation.\n81: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n82: - given: user enters search query\n83: - when: typing occurs in search input field\n84: - then: filter character display to show matching results in real-time\n85: - given: search input is empty\n86: - when: user submits without entering text\n87: - then: display validation message requiring input\n88: **Priority:** Must Have\n89: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:45-48\n90: \n91: ### FR-03: Character Like/Favorite System\n92: **Description:** Toggle functionality to mark characters as favorites with persistent visual feedback.\n93: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n94: - given: user views character gallery\n95: - when: user clicks like/favorite button on a character\n96: - then: toggle character's favorite status and update visual indicator\n97: - given: character is marked as favorite\n98: - when: page refreshes\n99: - then: favorite status should be maintained during session\n100: **Priority:** Should Have\n101: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:50-53\n102: \n103: ### FR-04: Character Deletion System\n104: **Description:** Remove characters from the display with appropriate user confirmation and visual feedback.\n105: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n106: - given: user wants to remove a character\n107: - when: user clicks delete button on character card\n108: - then: remove character from display with visual confirmation\n109: - given: character is deleted\n110: - when: user refreshes page\n111: - then: deleted character remains hidden during session\n112: **Priority:** Should Have\n113: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:50-53\n114: \n115: ### FR-05: Personalized Greeting System\n116: **Description:** Customizable greeting messages that update dynamically based on user interactions.\n117: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n118: - given: user interacts with application features\n119: - when: user performs significant actions (likes, searches, etc.)\n120: - then: update greeting message to reflect user activity\n121: - given: user customizes greeting\n122: - when: user enters custom message\n123: - then: display personalized greeting throughout session\n124: **Priority:** Could Have\n125: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:55-58\n126: \n127: ### FR-06: Dynamic Title Updates\n128: **Description:** Automatic page title updates based on user interactions and application state.\n129: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n130: - given: user performs various interactions in the application\n131: - when: significant application state changes occur\n132: - then: update browser tab title to reflect current context\n133: - given: user performs no interactions\n134: - when: page loads\n135: - then: display default application title\n136: **Priority:** Could Have\n137: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:55-58\n138: \n139: ### FR-07: Interactive Character Selection\n140: **Description:** Click functionality to select characters for detailed interaction and information display.\n141: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n142: - given: user views character gallery\n143: - when: user clicks on a character card\n144: - then: highlight selected character and show additional information\n145: - given: character is selected\n146: - when: user clicks another character\n147: - then: update selection to new character and hide previous details\n148: **Priority:** Should Have\n149: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:40-44\n150: \n151: ## Non-Functional Requirements\n152: \n153: ### NFR-01: Browser Compatibility\n154: **Description:** Application must function across modern web browsers.\n155: **Metric:** Browser support matrix compliance\n156: **Target:** Chrome 90+, Firefox 88+, Safari 14+, Edge 90+ with full feature support\n157: **Measurement Method:** Automated cross-browser testing with compatibility matrix validation\n158: **Priority:** Must Have\n159: source: context-pack/technical-requirements.md#lines:140-148\n160: \n161: ### NFR-02: Performance Loading Time\n162: **Description:** Fast initial page load for optimal user experience.\n163: **Metric:** Page load time\n164: **Target:** < 3 seconds for complete application load\n165: **Measurement Method:** Performance monitoring tools (Lighthouse, WebPageTest)\n166: **Priority:** Must Have\n167: source: context-pack/technical-requirements.md#lines:128-133\n168: \n169: ### NFR-03: Responsive Design\n170: **Description:** Application must adapt to different viewport sizes.\n171: **Metric:** Layout adaptation at break points\n172: **Target:** Functional layout at 820px+ viewport width\n173: **Measurement Method:** Visual regression testing across viewport sizes\n174: **Priority:** Must Have\n175: source: context-pack/technical-requirements.md#lines:70-74\n176: \n177: ### NFR-04: Animation Performance\n178: **Description:** Smooth visual transitions and hover effects.\n179: **Metric:** Frames per second for animations\n180: **Target:** 60fps CSS transitions for all interactive elements\n181: **Measurement Method:** Chrome DevTools Performance profiler\n182: **Priority:** Should Have\n183: source: context-pack/technical-requirements.md#lines:135-139\n184: \n185: ### NFR-05: Client-Side Security\n186: **Description:** Protection against common web vulnerabilities.\n187: **Metric:** Security vulnerability assessment\n188: **Target:** OWASP Top 10 compliance through static analysis scanning\n189: **Measurement Method:** Automated security scanning (SAST tools)\n190: ---\n191: version: 1.0.0\n192: session_id: RESEARCH-STARWARSLEGO-PRODUCTDEFINITION-20260703\n193: engagement_mode: greenfield\n194: skill: researching-prd\n195: generated_at: 2026-07-03T15:25:00.000Z\n196: ---\n197: \n198: # PRD SPEC: Star Wars Lego Educational Web Application\n199: \n200: ## Scope\n201: \n202: **Project Vision:** Create an engaging single-page web application that teaches JavaScript ES6+ and Vue.js 2.x concepts through interactive Star Wars Lego themed exercises.\n203: \n204: **Product Category:** Educational Technology - Interactive Programming Tutorial\n205: \n206: **Target Platform:** Web browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge) on desktop and tablet (820px+)\n207: \n208: **Out of Scope:** \n209: - Mobile applications (resolutions below 820px)\n210: - Backend/database integration\n211: - User authentication systems\n212: - Social media integration\n213: - Multiplayer features\n214: \n215: **Core Value Proposition:** Hands-on learning of modern web development through an engaging, themed interactive experience that bridges theory and practical application.\n216: \n217: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:6-14\n218: \n219: ## Personas\n220: \n221: ### P-01: Beginner JavaScript Student\n222: **Role:** Primary user learning programming fundamentals\n223: **Attributes:**\n224: - Age: 16-35\n225: - Technical level: Novice to beginner programmers\n226: - Learning goals: Master JavaScript ES6+ and Vue.js basics\n227: - Motivation: Career change, skill development, academic learning\n228: - Pain points: Abstract programming concepts, lack of engaging learning materials\n229: **Device usage:** Desktop computers, tablets for practice\n230: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:14-15\n231: \n232: ### P-02: Web Development Learner\n233: **Role:** Self-taught developer expanding skillset\n234: **Attributes:**\n235: - Age: 20-40\n236: - Technical level: Some HTML/CSS knowledge, limited JavaScript experience\n237: - Learning goals: Practical application of modern JavaScript frameworks\n238: - Motivation: Portfolio building, job preparation, hobby development\n239: - Pain points: Fragmented learning resources, lack of hands-on projects\n240: **Device usage:** Primary desktop, occasional tablet\n241: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:14-15\n242: \n243: ### P-03: Programming Educator\n244: **Role:** Teacher or instructor using the application as teaching tool\n245: **Attributes:**\n246: - Age: 25-55\n247: - Technical level: Experienced developer or educator\n248: - Learning goals: Teaching resources, demonstration materials\n249: - Motivation: Student engagement, effective teaching tools\n250: - Pain points: Finding engaging, practical examples for students\n251: **Device usage:** Desktop for classroom presentations\n252: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:14-15\n253: \n254: ## Functional Requirements\n255: \n256: ### FR-01: Character Gallery Display\n257: **Description:** Grid-based display of 8 classic Star Wars Lego characters with interactive hover effects and visual transitions.\n258: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n259: - given: user accesses the application\n260: - when: the main page loads\n261: - then: display 8 Star Wars Lego characters in a grid layout\n262: - given: user hovers over a character card\n263: - when: cursor enters the character area\n264: - then: show enhanced visual effects and transitions\n265: **Priority:** Must Have\n266: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:40-44\n267: \n268: ### FR-02: Character Search System\n269: **Description:** Real-time filtering functionality to search characters by name with input validation.\n270: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n271: - given: user enters search query\n272: - when: typing occurs in search input field\n273: - then: filter character display to show matching results in real-time\n274: - given: search input is empty\n275: - when: user submits without entering text\n276: - then: display validation message requiring input\n277: **Priority:** Must Have\n278: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:45-48\n279: \n280: ### FR-03: Character Like/Favorite System\n281: **Description:** Toggle functionality to mark characters as favorites with persistent visual feedback.\n282: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n283: - given: user views character gallery\n284: - when: user clicks like/favorite button on a character\n285: - then: toggle character's favorite status and update visual indicator\n286: - given: character is marked as favorite\n287: - when: page refreshes\n288: - then: favorite status should be maintained during session\n289: **Priority:** Should Have\n290: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:50-53\n291: \n292: ### FR-04: Character Deletion System\n293: **Description:** Remove characters from the display with appropriate user confirmation and visual feedback.\n294: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n295: - given: user wants to remove a character\n296: - when: user clicks delete button on character card\n297: - then: remove character from display with visual confirmation\n298: - given: character is deleted\n299: - when: user refreshes page\n300: - then: deleted character remains hidden during session\n301: **Priority:** Should Have\n302: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:50-53\n303: \n304: ### FR-05: Personalized Greeting System\n305: **Description:** Customizable greeting messages that update dynamically based on user interactions.\n306: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n307: - given: user interacts with application features\n308: - when: user performs significant actions (likes, searches, etc.)\n309: - then: update greeting message to reflect user activity\n310: - given: user customizes greeting\n311: - when: user enters custom message\n312: - then: display personalized greeting throughout session\n313: **Priority:** Could Have\n314: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:55-58\n315: \n316: ### FR-06: Dynamic Title Updates\n317: **Description:** Automatic page title updates based on user interactions and application state.\n318: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n319: - given: user performs various interactions in the application\n320: - when: significant application state changes occur\n321: - then: update browser tab title to reflect current context\n322: - given: user performs no interactions\n323: - when: page loads\n324: - then: display default application title\n325: **Priority:** Could Have\n326: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:55-58\n327: \n328: ### FR-07: Interactive Character Selection\n329: **Description:** Click functionality to select characters for detailed interaction and information display.\n330: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n331: - given: user views character gallery\n332: - when: user clicks on a character card\n333: - then: highlight selected character and show additional information\n334: - given: character is selected\n335: - when: user clicks another character\n336: - then: update selection to new character and hide previous details\n337: **Priority:** Should Have\n338: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:40-44\n339: \n340: ## Non-Functional Requirements\n341: \n342: ### NFR-01: Browser Compatibility\n343: **Description:** Application must function across modern web browsers.\n344: **Metric:** Browser support matrix compliance\n345: **Target:** Chrome 90+, Firefox 88+, Safari 14+, Edge 90+ with full feature support\n346: **Measurement Method:** Automated cross-browser testing with compatibility matrix validation\n347: **Priority:** Must Have\n348: source: context-pack/technical-requirements.md#lines:140-148\n349: \n350: ### NFR-02: Performance Loading Time\n351: **Description:** Fast initial page load for optimal user experience.\n352: **Metric:** Page load time\n353: **Target:** < 3 seconds for complete application load\n354: **Measurement Method:** Performance monitoring tools (Lighthouse, WebPageTest)\n355: **Priority:** Must Have\n356: source: context-pack/technical-requirements.md#lines:128-133\n357: \n358: ### NFR-03: Responsive Design\n359: **Description:** Application must adapt to different viewport sizes.\n360: **Metric:** Layout adaptation at break points\n361: **Target:** Functional layout at 820px+ viewport width\n362: **Measurement Method:** Visual regression testing across viewport sizes\n363: **Priority:** Must Have\n364: source: context-pack/technical-requirements.md#lines:70-74\n365: \n366: ### NFR-04: Animation Performance\n367: **Description:** Smooth visual transitions and hover effects.\n368: **Metric:** Frames per second for animations\n369: **Target:** 60fps CSS transitions for all interactive elements\n370: **Measurement Method:** Chrome DevTools Performance profiler\n371: **Priority:** Should Have\n372: source: context-pack/technical-requirements.md#lines:135-139\n373: \n374: ### NFR-05: Client-Side Security\n375: **Description:** Protection against common web vulnerabilities.\n376: **Metric:** Security vulnerability assessment\n377: **Target:** OWASP Top 10 compliance through static analysis scanning\n378: **Measurement Method:** Automated security scanning (SAST tools)\n379: **Priority:** Must Have\n380: source: context-pack/technical-requirements.md#lines:155-162\n381: \n382: ### NFR-06: Code Quality Standards\n383: **Description:** Maintainable, well-documented educational code.\n384: **Metric:** Code analysis metrics\n385: **Target:** 90%+ code documentation coverage, modular component structure\n386: **Measurement Method:** Code analysis tools, peer review checklists\n387: **Priority:** Should Have\n388: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:121-126\n389: \n390: ### NFR-07: Search Performance\n391: **Description:** Efficient real-time filtering of character data.\n392: **Metric:** Filter response time\n393: **Target:** < 100ms response time for search operations on 8 character dataset\n394: **Measurement Method:** Performance profiling of search/filter functions\n395: **Priority:** Should Have\n396: source: context-pack/technical-requirements.md#lines:135-139\n397: \n398: ### NFR-08: Visual Design Consistency\n399: **Description:** Consistent Star Wars themed visual appearance.\n400: **Metric:** Design system compliance\n401: **Target:** 100% compliance with specified color palette and typography\n402: **Measurement Method:** Visual regression testing against design specifications\n403: **Priority:** Should Have\n404: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:62-69\n405: \n406: ## KPIs\n407: \n408: ### KPI-01: Learning Engagement Rate\n409: **Description:** Measure of user interaction with educational features.\n410: **Metric:** Interaction events per session\n411: **Target:** Average 10+ interactions per user session\n412: **Measurement Method:** Track user clicks, searches, and feature usage\n413: **Priority:** Must Have\n414: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:16-21\n415: \n416: ### KPI-02: Concept Demonstration Effectiveness\n417: **Description:** Success rate of JavaScript concepts demonstration.\n418: **Metric:** Completion rate of interactive exercises\n419: **Target:** 80% of users complete at least one full interaction cycle\n420: **Measurement Method:** Track user journey completion paths\n421: **Priority:** Should Have\n422: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:16-21\n423: \n424: ### KPI-03: Search Functionality Usage\n425: **Description:** Frequency of character search feature usage.\n426: **Metric:** Search queries per session\n427: **Target:** Average 3+ search queries per active session\n428: **Measurement Method:** Track search input events and result interactions\n429: **Priority:** Should Have\n430: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:45-48\n431: \n432: ### KPI-04: Performance Accessibility\n433: **Description:** Load time performance across different network conditions.\n434: **Metric:** Load time compliance percentage\n435: **Target:** 95% of sessions load within 3-second target\n436: **Measurement Method:** Real User Monitoring (RUM) data collection\n437: **Priority:** Must Have\n438: source: context-pack/technical-requirements.md#lines:128-133\n439: \n440: ### KPI-05: Browser Compatibility Coverage\n441: **Description:** Success rate across supported browser matrix.\n442: **Metric:** Browser success rate\n443: **Target:** 98% functionality success across Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge\n444: **Measurement Method:** Automated cross-browser testing and error reporting\n445: **Priority:** Must Have\n446: source: context-pack/technical-requirements.md#lines:140-148\n447: \n448: ### KPI-06: Code Learning Retention\n449: **Description:** User retention of demonstrated programming concepts.\n450: **Metric:** Return visit frequency\n451: **Target:** 40% of users return within 7 days for additional practice\n452: **Measurement Method:** User session tracking and analytics\n453: **Priority:** Could Have\n454: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:115-119\n455: \n456: ## Jobs-To-Be-Done (JTBD)\n457: \n458: ### JTBD-01: Learn JavaScript Fundamentals\n459: **Who:** Beginner JavaScript Student (P-01)\n460: **What:** Master practical JavaScript ES6+ concepts through hands-on interaction\n461: **Why:** Bridge the gap between theoretical knowledge and real-world application development\n462: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:16-18\n463: \n464: ### JTBD-02: Understand Vue.js Reactivity\n465: **Who:** Web Development Learner (P-02)\n466: **What:** Learn Vue.js 2.x data binding and component patterns through interactive examples\n467: **Why:** Apply modern frontend development framework knowledge to practical projects\n468: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:18-19\n469: \n470: ### JTBD-03: Practice DOM Manipulation\n471: **Who:** Beginner JavaScript Student (P-01)\n472: **What:** Gain experience with dynamic HTML element modification and event handling\n473: **Why:** Build confidence in creating interactive web applications beyond static pages\n474: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:20\n475: \n476: ### JTBD-04: Demonstrate Programming Concepts to Students\n477: **Who:** Programming Educator (P-03)\n478: **What:** Use engaging interactive examples to teach abstract programming concepts\n479: **Why:** Increase student engagement and comprehension through practical, relatable examples\n480: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:14-15\n481: \n482: ### JTBD-05: Apply ES6+ Features Practically\n483: **Who:** Web Development Learner (P-02)\n484: **What:** Practice using arrow functions, array methods, and object patterns in real scenarios\n485: **Why:** Transition from theoretical knowledge to practical coding ability\n486: source: context-pack/technical-requirements.md#lines:44-50\n487: \n488: ### JTBD-06: Create Portfolio-Worthy Projects\n489: **Who:** Web Development Learner (P-02)\n490: **What:** Build interactive components that demonstrate modern web development skills\n491: **Why:** Create evidence of practical ability for job applications and career advancement\n492: source: context-pack/project-overview.md#lines:14-15\n493: \n494: ## Traceability\n495: \n496: ### Forward Traceability (FR → JTBD)\n497: \n498: | FR ID | JTBD ID(s) | Status |\n499: |-------|------------|--------|\n500: | FR-01 | JTBD-01, JTBD-03, JTBD-05 | mapped |\n\n[File truncated at 500 lines for safety. Use offset/limit to paginate.]", "metadata": {"start_line": 1, "end_line": 500, "returned_lines": 500, "has_more": true, "eof_reached": false, "truncated": true}}}
